Data Structure:

     ADT: 
     
     Since Gerp involves a nuanced amount of different data structures,
     we will be organizing this section into two compartments, one being
     how we access a certain word given an index, and returning the hash 
     index, and the other being the data structure that stores our files and
     file contents. We start from the "lowest" level of data structure, and
     work up to the organization of said data structure.

     File Content Storage: 
     
                       pair <string,bool>
     
     1. Our lowest data structure contains a pair. The first component is a 
     string that represents string of a unique line Content of a particular 
     file. The boolean variable represents whether or not the line has been 
     seen or not. The reason why we included this variance is because for 
     cases where theres duplicates of a word in the same line, we do not
     output that line more than once. Additionally, the boolean makes it 
     the insensitive duplicate case much more managable, because if we
     come across the same line more than once, setting the seen bool to true 
     allows it to skip it over
     
              vector < pair <string,bool> >
     
     2. The next level to the File Content is a vector. This vector represents
     all the lines in a unique, single file.

     vector < vector < pair <string,bool> > >      

     3. Lastly, the outer most vector represents a vector of all the possible
     files are in a given directory. 

     Reset Vector:
      
              pair <int, int>

     1. The pair stores two integers which stores the file number and a line 
     number. This is so that we can just reset the boolean in the file content 
     after a query has processed  

     vector < pair <int, int> > resetChecker;

     2.  For instance, if A
     given word, let the word be "cat", is repeated numerous times in a line 
     in numerous occasions throughout a directory, then the resetChecker will 
     go through the "coordinates" of a given line, and reset the boolean 
     in the vectorFiles data structure, for the entirety of the size of the 
     resetChecker vector. Afterwards, we can just clear the vector after a 
     queue.

     hashTable Implementation: 
     
     We used the hashMap functionality to access a given word within O(1) time.
                      <Sentence>
     
     1. Sentence is a struct definition that contains two integers, the file 
     number and line number, and the word in the text without conversions. We 
     made this a class definition in order for both our gerp class and our 
     hashMap class to know the same constraints of the sentence struct.

               vector <Sentence>
     
     2. We have a vector of sentence structs because given a word in a file, 
     there are numerous instances of that word being in a sentence.

     pair < string, vector<Sentence>>* hashVector; 
     
     3. Lastly, we have a pair that stores all of these sentence structs! The
     string is the inputted word from the text, stripped of non-Alpha numeric 
     characters, and lowercased completely. The reason we chose this approach 
     to combining sensitive and insensitive cases is that it makes insensitive 
     cases infinitely easier to produce, and in the worst case for sensitive, 
     it has to iterate through all the sentence strucut and access the word,
     and then output it. We decided that because we group both cases into one 
     bucket of the hashVector, it takes a lot less time to index with the 
     tradeoff being slower query time for sensitive cases.

     Algorithm: 

          ProcessLine(): 
     
     This function makes it so that when we store a certain 
     word and its file and line number, it first lowercases the given word,
     and passes it to the insertHash() function that puts it in our hash Table.
     What is interesting with this algorithm is that it purposely groups all 
     combinations of a certain word together in a given bucket, making 
     insensitive cases really easy.

          Index Content():

     The algorithm behind this is how we make the vector not 0 indexed anymore.
     At the beginning of the function, we push the path of the line as the 
     first element in the vector of lines. Accordingly, this makes it so that
     we need to always access the 0th element for the path, and the subsequent
     position of a line in a given file index. 

          ReHash():
     
     We update the size of the Hash table and create new memory on the heap 
     that our hashVector points to. Iterating through the old size of the Hash
     Vector, we access the string and vector of sentence, use the hash function
     to access the index. We first need to check if accessing a given index of
     the old hashVector is empty since we do not need to rehash those values. 
     Sequentially, we check for the case where when rehashing, we also run into
     a collision. If so, update the index. Finally, add that old pair into 
     the new Hashmap, delete the old HashMap, and make HashVector point to 
     the new Hashmap.

          resetSeen():
     
     This algorithm was used to reset our boolean inside our pairs in the vector
     of files. Given a vector of pairs, we were able to deduce the same line of
     reasoning with accessing a specific file and line number, and reset that 
     specific checker. The reason why we chose a vector to store the pair is so
     that when there is multiple duplicates for an insensitive case. At first, 
     our initial thought was that using an array that stored the index of what 
     file number we need to reset would take too much time as not every line 
     within a file will be seen given a word.Consequently, using the coordinate 
     approach, we allocated a vector that stored the "seen" coordinates, reset 
     the bool, then cleared the vector for later use.

          getHashVector():

     This function firstly checks if a given word stripped of non-alpha numeric 
     characters is a length of size 0. The reason behind is because we do not 
     want our program to think that the input command is just " " and print 
     every line with a space. It then iterates through the entire array 
     until the associated word has been found; however, we do not want it 
     to traverse through the array more than once, so we have a conditional 
     that checks if the index % hashSize == to the initial index itself.

*******************************************************************************

Testing:

     Unit Testing:

          We use the unit test framework to verify the functionality of 
          stripping non-alphabetic characters from strings, traversing 
          directories, storing content from files, and inserting key-value 
          pairs into a hashmap. The reasoning behind using unit testing 
          for this approach is that we want to test the basic functions of our
          larger framework, and for testing the output statements when running 
          our program, diffing makes it more logical.

          stripNonAlphaNum: 
          
          We used unit testing with this function since the only
          parameters it can take are strings, a variable type that is easy
          to unit test to and compare with. We declared the combinations that
          are possible with the input that the user could choose: A normal 
          input, non-Alphanumeric characters in the front, non-Alphanumeric
          characters at the back of the input, both the front and back, and 
          in between the given input to ensure that testing is done thorough 
          and the function is general for all query cases.

     Test directory traversal with the following test directories:

          - onlyFiles: A directory created to test conditions where only files 
          are present in the directory provided to the program.
          - onlySubDir: A directory created to test conditions where only 
          subdirectories are present in the directory provided to the program.
          - empty: An empty directory created to test conditions where no files 
          or subdirectories are present.

     Test the gerp program:

          We test the program using all command files provided in 
          proj-gerp-sample-execution on the small, medium, and large Gutenberg 
          directories. For each test, we compare our output file with the 
          output from reference program using the diff command. Additionally, 
          we test the @f command by comparing both first and second output 
          files with the output from reference program.

     Test for the inability to open input or output files:

          - Input file: Test by restricting the permissions of files in the 
            testing directory with "chmod 000" command and modify the error 
            message to match the output from the reference program.
          - First output file: We noticed that the error message for failing to 
            open the first output file appears before the message for the input 
            file, so we adjust the order in which the files are opened.
          - Output file provided with the @f command: We found that the error 
            message for this file includes the file name, so we ensure that it
            is printed correctly.

     Edge Cases:

          Additional test and command files are created to cover edge cases:
          - Nonexistent directory name: To properly exit the program when given 
            an invalid directory name, we catch the runtime error from the 
            FSTree constructor and print the error message.
          - Empty files in provided directory
          - Multi-word query
          - Entirely non-alphanumeric input
          - Single character string input
          - Using @f command multiple times: Test by comparing all output files
            with reference output files
          - If a word exists in a different form (For example, Hi is in small
            gutenberg but hi isn't), make sure to print out word isn't found if
            user inputs hi

     Runtime and memory usage: 

          We use the gerp_perf command to check our runtime and memory usage 
          to ensure they are within the specified limits. Something to note was 
          that intially, our gerp used 6.06 GB of ram. We searched up and found 
          that by choosing an initial Hash Size to be a prime number, less 
          collisions can occur, reducing the total amount of space needed for
          our hash table. For example, if we made our hashSize to be 10 or 20,
          there will be more numbers modded with 10 or 20 that have the same 
          value in contrary to modding with 11 or 23.

